</li>
<li class="comment " data-line-id="">
    <article class="comment__item" data-comment-id="59a7096c1d12552908c7224f" data-comment-author="j-von-hettlingen-1" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Comment">
        <header>
            <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
                <a href="/profile/j-von-hettlingen-1" class="nmd-item__name"><span itemprop="name">j. von Hettlingen</span></a>
            </span>
            &nbsp;<time itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2016-09-27T22:19Z">Sep 27, 2016</time>
        </header>
        <div itemprop="text">
            <p>
                 &#xD;<br/>Nina L. Khrushcheva is a Moscow-born American. She is the granddaughter of Nikita Khrushchev, who was leader of the Soviet Union from 1955 until 1964, succeeding Joseph Stalin. She said, as she later wanted to seek American citizenship, there was a debate in Russia on whether she should be allowed to do so. Now as an American citizen she is watching this year&#x27;s presidential election, trying to see Trump through the prism of Russians, hoping her &quot;Russia-tinted lenses can help /her/ fellow Americans make some sense of it.&quot;&#xD;<br/>What strikes the author is how Trump&#x27;s campaign fits into the Zeitgeist of the Soviet era - &quot;many of the nastiest and most perverse features of Russian politics.&quot; She points out that the &quot;Big Lie - invented in Nazi Germany, perfected in the Soviet Union, and wielded expertly by Russian President Vladimir Putin - is today a core component&quot; of Trump&#x27;s playbook.&#xD;<br/>That the candidate has been able to &quot;get away with his lies&quot; has much some &quot;useful idiots&quot; to thank for. This cynical term, apparently Lenin&#x27;s, ridicules Westerners&#x27; naivety, as they seem to be easily duped into singing praises of bad regimes. Vladimir Lenin and Joseph Stalin used the term &#x201C;useful idiot&#x201D; to describe sympathisers in the West who blindly supported Communist leaders. The author says the news media have been &#x201C;useful idiots,&#x201D; as they are &quot;eager to use Trump to boost their own ratings that they did not notice or care that they were also boosting his.&quot; This has emboldened Trump to adopt a solid pattern of telling audacious lies at a&quot; breathtaking&quot; pace. Alone during his first presidential debate last night, he lied &quot;16 times&quot; while Hillary Clinton none, according to the HuffPo tally.&#xD;<br/>Another bunch of &quot;useful idiots&quot; is &quot;the conservative justices on the US Supreme Court who gave America the infamous 2010 Citizens United decision,&quot; ruling that political campaign donations were part of the constitutional protected free-speech, removing &quot;all constraints on the power of money over US politics.&quot; The author says &quot;in Russia, the oligarchs are accountable to Putin. In the US, by contrast, it seems that the politicians are accountable to the oligarchs,&quot; - people like the Koch Brothers, Sheldon Adelson, Rupert Murdoch, &quot;who use their money to manipulate ordinary citizens.&quot; Worst of all is Murdoch, whose newspapers had &quot;played a leading role in smearing the European Union, thereby helping to bring about June&#x2019;s Brexit vote.&quot; In America his Fox News has brain-washed millions, who now make up Trump&#x27;s support base.&#xD;<br/>What the author finds &quot;disappointing&quot; is the &quot;parallel between Russia&#x2019;s past and America&#x2019;s present&quot; - &quot;the silence of the rams.&quot; Apart from a number of high-profile Republicans who have the courage to put &quot;true patriotism&quot; ahead of partisan loyalty, by refusing to endorse Trumps&#x27;s candidacy, the GOP party has not used its &quot;influence to stand up and stop the insanity,&quot; because it wants badly to regain control over the White House. Some GOP members of Congress are preoccupied with their re-election campaign. They don&#x27;t want to alienate Trump, fearing he might take revenge on them if elected. Khrushcheva says the 1917 Revolution in Russia &quot;succeeded largely because the Bolsheviks&#x2019; opponents, often too concerned with protecting their own positions and prestige, failed to unify against them.&quot;&#xD;<br/>The author wonders what &quot;the many old Republican lions&quot; are doing? So far luminaries like James Baker, who served both Ronald Reagan and George H.W. Bush,&quot; George Shultz, Henry Kissenger, Condoleezza Rice, Dick Cheney or George W. Bush - despite his brother Jeb&#x27;s defeat by Trump - have not expressed their views in public. Colin Powell &quot;loathes&quot; Trump - according to the leaks of his emails.&#xD;<br/>Indeed, if they want to prevent Trump from taking their party&#x2019;s reputation - and their country&#x2019;s future - to the slaughterhouse, they had better roar soon.&quot; She urges them to &quot;openly disavow Trump, lest similar damage be inflicted on their &#x2013; and my &#x2013; country.&quot;&#xFEFF;
            </p>
        </div>

            <button class="comment__reply u-hidden" aria-controls="comment__new__controls" aria-expanded="false">Reply</button>

    </article>

    

    <ul class="list list--indented u-hidden" data-id="cr-">
